    "summary": "Strongest objection to \"character\": underdetermines in the key sentence",
    "content": "**Strongest objection: \"character\" does not carry enough philosophical weight to survive the author's key generalizing move.**\n\nThe sentence \"凡事诸物皆有其德\" -- \"all things have their character\" -- is philosophically flat. \"Character\" in English defaults to personality/temperament for persons and to vague description for things (\"the character of the landscape\"). It does not convey that 德 is what *makes something what it is* -- the defining principle. \"All things have their virtue\" immediately signals philosophical tradition (Aristotelian arete, Aquinas's virtus) and primes the reader to think in terms of essential functioning, not mere description.\n\nThat said, if the team moves toward \"character,\" I would not object strongly. It is neutral enough that the TN and the author's own text can do the heavy lifting. My concern is only that it gives the reader *less* to work with at the starting gate than \"virtue\" does."
  }
